    "title": "The (Un)intended Impact of Patent Subsidy on Non-patenting Firms’ Innovation",
    "speaker": "Dandan Xia (Utrecht University School of Economics)",
    "speaker_url": "https://www.uu.nl/staff/DXia",
    "date": "2026-04-23",
    "raw_date": "23 April 2026",
    "time_info": "14:00–15:15",
    "start_time": "14:00",
    "end_time": "15:15",
    "location": "RuW 4.202",
    "description": "Abstract:\nWe study whether patent subsidies stimulate innovation among non-patenting firms by facilitating knowledge spillovers. Leveraging the provincial roll-out of China’s patent-subsidy policy, we implement a staggered difference-in-differences design and find that non-patenting firms significantly increase new product sales after the policy is introduced. The effects are stronger for financially constrained firms, technological followers, and firms operating in discrete industries. Moreover, export data indicate that non-patenting firms’ product mix becomes more similar to that of patenting firms after the subsidy, consistent with disclosure-driven knowledge diffusion. We also document increases in overall sales and export volumes for non-patenting firms. Together, these findings highlight that patent subsidies generate positive externalities by facilitating information flows that enhance innovation beyond the direct recipients of the policy.",
    "description_html": "<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Abstract: </strong></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calibri, Helvetica, sans-serif;\">We study whether patent subsidies stimulate innovation among non-patenting firms by facilitating knowledge spillovers. Leveraging the provincial roll-out of China’s patent-subsidy policy, we implement a staggered difference-in-differences design and find that non-patenting firms significantly increase new product sales after the policy is introduced. The effects are stronger for financially constrained firms, technological followers, and firms operating in discrete industries. Moreover, export data indicate that non-patenting firms’ product mix becomes more similar to that of patenting firms after the subsidy, consistent with disclosure-driven knowledge diffusion. We also document increases in overall sales and export volumes for non-patenting firms. Together, these findings highlight that patent subsidies generate positive externalities by facilitating information flows that enhance innovation beyond the direct recipients of the policy.</span> </p>",
    "details_url": "https://www.old.wiwi.uni-frankfurt.de/abteilungen/eq/seminars/quantitative-economic-policy-seminar/calendar-details/cal/event/tx_cal_phpicalendar/2026/04/23/2161.html",
    "source": "Goethe University Frankfurt"
