    "seminar_page": "https://www.old.wiwi.uni-frankfurt.de/abteilungen/eq/seminars/quantitative-economic-policy-seminar.html",
    "title": "(Equivalized) Spending Changes at Widowhood",
    "speaker": "Bertrand Achou (University of Groningen)",
    "speaker_url": "https://sites.google.com/site/bertrandachou/home",
    "date": "2026-04-30",
    "raw_date": "30 April 2026",
    "time_info": "14:00–15:15",
    "start_time": "14:00",
    "end_time": "15:15",
    "location": "RuW 4.202",
    "description": "Abstract:\nUsing data from the Health and Retirement Study (HRS) and the Consumption and Activities Mail Survey (CAMS), we examine how widowhood affects spending—particularly equivalized spending—among US retirees. Applying standard equivalence scale values, we find that equivalized spending increases at widowhood. We then compare this finding to theoretical predictions about equivalized spending from different versions of the life cycle model, varying, for instance, in the ability to insure against widowhood risk. Through this analysis, we aim to determine the conditions under which such a phenomenon can arise and explore its potential implications for the adequacy of annuity and life insurance demand, as well as Social Security survivor benefits.",
    "description_html": "<p><strong>Abstract: </strong></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica;\">Using data from the Health and Retirement Study (HRS) and the Consumption and Activities Mail Survey (CAMS), we examine how widowhood affects spending—particularly equivalized spending—among US retirees. Applying standard equivalence scale values, we find that equivalized spending increases at widowhood. We then compare this finding to theoretical predictions about equivalized spending from different versions of the life cycle model, varying, for instance, in the ability to insure against widowhood risk. Through this analysis, we aim to determine the conditions under which such a phenomenon can arise and explore its potential implications for the adequacy of annuity and life insurance demand, as well as Social Security survivor benefits.</span></p>",
    "details_url": "https://www.old.wiwi.uni-frankfurt.de/abteilungen/eq/seminars/quantitative-economic-policy-seminar/calendar-details/cal/event/tx_cal_phpicalendar/2026/04/30/2162.html",
    "source": "Goethe University Frankfurt"
